onsiders how distinctly local white-power scenes have emerged in Western Europe, Eastern Europe, Latin America, the United States, and many other sites. While exploring how white-power bands draw from a common well of nationalist, racist, and neo-Nazi ideologies, the book thus also illuminates how white-power musicians adapt their music to different locations, many of which have their own terms for defining whiteness and racial otherness. Closely tracking the online presence of white-power musicians and their fans, Dyck analyzes the virtual forums and media they use to articulate their hateful rhetoric. This book also demonstrates how this fandom has sparked spectacular violence in the real world, from bombings to mass shootings. Reichsrock thus sounds an urgent message about a global menace.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aHate groups. 0aHeavy metal (Music)xPolitical aspects. 0aHeavy metal (Music)xSocial aspects. 0aNeo-Nazism. 0aPunk rock musicxPolitical aspects. 0aPunk rock musicxSocial aspects. 0aWhite supremacy movements. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081357473840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813574738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813574738.jpg  a978-3-11-066614-4  RUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK